d</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Benson</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE011152%2F1"><gtr:id>EE503C88-9E4D-4357-AE76-D99E908D97AE</gtr:id><gtr:title>Task allocation in European Union environmental policy: testing the value of a federal theoretical perspective</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E011152/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The European Union (EU) is 50 years old - but what exactly has it evolved into? Over this period, Member States have progressively pooled sovereignty to create a powerful political system, determining the actions of 500 million citizens. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>A significant academic and public debate has arisen over the extent to which this system can be considered federal. National politicians have promoted the spectre of a federal Europe to justify resistance to further integration, particularly in the recent constitutional process. Scholars are promoting federal theories to explain EU integration, with an emergent ?federal turn? apparent in such research. Yet, claims that the EU is becoming federal directly challenge well-established theoretical approaches viewing the EU as a trade-based international organisation or unique political entity. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The research aims to explore these claims. It will examine federal arguments within one leading sub-sector of EU policy-making, namely environmental policy. Using evidence from documentary sources and interviewing of policy-makers, the research will seek to understand how powers (?tasks?) are allocated between political levels: a critical characteristic of federalism. An assessment on the value of federal arguments to the wider EU integration debate can then be made. Findings will be disseminated to an academic and non-academic audience.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-04-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-05-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>67705</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/E011152/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>EBACD6D4-D1E5-4970-8BEC-7F4568EB26BA</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Development studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>E844174D-6A1C-4D2D-8F24-57698F7DA353</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Environmental planning</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>4511FB20-8392-418E-809D-7701FACC03C9</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Law